Narrator

The Maroon Palace was bustling with activity as party leaders and their entourages filed in one by one to discuss the latest changes to the constitutional reform proposal.

Albin Clavin

"We did. And we have some concerns."

Gloria Tory

"Very funny, Mr. Rayne."

Gloria Tory

"Especially after the whole party gave you the necessary signatures to open the constitutional reform process."

Player

"I understand your concerns, but I stand by my decision. Let's talk about how I can convince you to support me."

Gloria Tory

"You already knew you had no support from the party. Yet you push this ridiculous change at the last minute, knowing you will fail."

Gloria Tory

"Mr. Rayne. I'm not sure if you understand. You can't sweet talk your way out of this."

Player

"Come on, Ms. Tory. Let's be reasonable."

Player

"What is the meaning of this?"

Player

"You are not the USP, Ms. Tory. You can't speak on behalf of everyone like this."

Gloria Tory

"You can't be that naive, Mr. Rayne. We suspect you have different ambitions."

Player

"You're right, I'm not that naive. I wouldn't have gone with this if I didn't believe we could pass it."

Gloria Tory

"Do you want us to believe that?"

Player

"Am I the one who's deflecting? Are you really going to ignore the discrimination our Bludish citizens face in Sordland?"

Player

"Tell me. What can I do for you? Is there nothing that will convince you otherwise?"

Gloria Tory

"You are acknowledging the aims of the secessionists by agreeing with their baseless arguments. Are you really claiming Article 6 is what started the terror?"

Gloria Tory

"Don't try to pin that on Article 6. This is about what this country is, about Sords and about unity."

Narrator

She snorted derisively.

Player

"How is enshrining equal rights for everyone against this nation, Mr. Tory? I didn't expect you to be this blinded by ethno-nationalism."

Player

"The Bludish community wants to be recognized by the state. We should no longer ignore their culture and identity."

Gloria Tory

"Don't throw words around like that. I'm not a supporter of anti-Bludism and I'm definitely not what you're labeling me as."

Player

"I'm not saying Article 6 is the sole cause, but it's one of the reasons nonetheless. If millions of Bludish people demand this change, we should listen to them."

Player

"The party will evolve, whether you like it or not."

Gloria Tory

"So, accepting everyone as Sords regardless of their ethnicity instead of dividing the nation into subgroups is racist?"

Player

"So be it, Ms. Tory."

Player

"Mr. Clavin, how about you? You call yourself a reformist, don't you? This is the time to act like one."

Player

"The BFF lost the support of the Bludish people. We have new channels of intelligence about them, their plans and their leadership. If this proposal goes through, the Bludish movement will aid us in destroying them."

Gloria Tory

"The Workers Party of Bludia?"

Player

"Please stop with this attitude, Ms. Tory. They deserve to be recognized. The BFF didn't appear out of nowhere. Did you ever ask yourselves if maybe you're to blame?"

Gloria Tory

"You did not just say that."

Narrator

I've heard hushed whispers among the party leaders.

Gloria Tory

"In order for us to even start talking about a possible deal, you have to first remove your changes to the election threshold and reinstate the Member of Honor rights for Tarquin Soll."

Player

"What are your concerns? Let's try to find some common ground."

Gloria Tory

"In order for us to even start talking about a possible deal, you have to first remove your changes to the election threshold."

Player

"Will that ensure your support?"

Player

"But you already agreed to those points, Ms. Tory. Please don't be unreasonable."

Gloria Tory

"No. It won't. This is only the proposal, Mr. Rayne. We may yet have other requests."

Player

"Will that ensure your support?"

Player

"But you already agreed to that point before, Ms. Tory. Please don't be unreasonable."

Gloria Tory

"No. It won't. This is only the proposal, Mr. Rayne. We may yet have other requests."

Player

"No. I can't do that. There will be no deals."

Player

"Will that ensure your support?"

Player

"But you already agreed to that point before, Ms. Tory. Please don't be unreasonable."

"No. I can't do that. There will be no deals."

Player

"This is a mistake."

"Then it's time for us to leave."

"This is a mistake."

Player

"This is a mistake."

"The USP is not happy with the changes you made to the Energy Protection Act. You turned it into an Energy Exploitation Act."

Gloria Tory

"You opened the way for foreign powers to control half of our energy industry. This is not something we can accept."

Gloria Tory

You opened way for the foreign powers to control our energy industry. This is not something we can accept."

Gloria Tory

"This is not something we can accept."

Gloria Tory

"We were absolutely furious to learn about your plans to give semi-autonomy to Bergia."

"After we confirm the integrity of the intelligence, you will arrest Fetih Ejall for harboring connections to the BFF and withholding information from the state."

Player

"Mr. Ejall is helping us. I can't agree to arrest him. This conflicts with our aim of earning the support of the Bludish populace."

Player

"Fine. I agree to all of your demands. I'll revert the Energy Protection Act, cancel the semi-autonomous zone and arrest Mr. Ejall."

Player

"I can't stop the work on the semi-autonomous zone now. This goes hand in hand with our reform proposal."

Gloria Tory

"That will simply not work, Mr. Rayne."

Gloria Tory

"Either you agree with our demands or there is no deal."

Gloria Tory

"So you agree with our other demands?"

Gloria Tory

"That is a red line for us, Mr. Rayne. You have to stop it."

Player

"I can't do that."

Player

"I can't do that."

Gloria Tory

"You know what? If you're willing to do that, we'll have a deal."

Player

"On second thought, I'm not really sure."

Player

"Fine. I agree to all of your demands. I'll revert the Energy Protection Act and order the arrest of Mr. Ejall."

Gloria Tory

"Then you can get your support from elsewhere, Mr. Rayne."

Gloria Tory

"I'm sure you can take it."

Narrator

She sighed.

Gloria Tory

"If you say so, Mr. Rayne. You can say goodbye to your reform package."

Gloria Tory

"Not even a gesture of respect... Please don't embarrass yourself any longer, Mr. Rayne. You still carry the name of the party."

Narrator

After shaking hands, Gloria, together with the rest of the leadership and their entourage, left the office.

Gloria Tory

"Good luck finding votes for your *reforms.* Not even your pert vice president can help you with it now."

Player

"To be completely honest, I think we're screwed."

Player

"I'm sorry, Petr. I think I pushed the party too far. We may need to say goodbye to our reforms."

Petr Vectern

"I told you we can't trust anyone except each other, Anton. We knew we were always on our own."

Petr Vectern

"But don't worry. We'll find a way out of this. Just like we always have."

Player

"I wish I could be that optimistic."

Player

"It's going to be difficult with the USP breathing down our necks."

Narrator

For a second, I sensed desperation in his eyes.

Petr Vectern

"You know I'll always be there for you, Anton."

Petr Vectern

"Lighten up now."

Player

"Amazing. The whole party promised to vote for the proposal."

Player

"They pushed me around and I had to compromise, but it worked out in the end."

Player

"We made a deal, but I still don't trust them. It looked like they were uniting against us."

Player

"It didn't go as planned. We made a deal, but it seems like the party is uniting under Ms. Tory now. She may be their next candidate."

Petr Vectern

"She's a central figure, but I doubt the party considers her candidate material."

Petr Vectern

"I was suspecting the same. There is a lot of movement in the party these days."

Petr Vectern

"You did it!?"

Petr Vectern

"That's a relief."

Narrator

Petr took a look at his watch.

Player

"Great. As if the party wasn't enough... I hope he didn't change his mind as well."

Player

"I'm sure he'll be delighted hear the whole USP is behind the proposal."

Narrator

Petr took a look at his watch.

Player

"Great. As if the party wasn't enough... I don't know if the PFJP can even help us anymore."

Player

"Honestly, I'd rather have them lead the reforms than our party. I hope to be the last USP president in this country."

Petr Vectern

"Are you serious?"

Petr Vectern

"Don't be like that, Anton. It is not the end of the world. We're still here, aren't we?"

Narrator

Suddenly, Livia informed us about Frens Ricter's arrival.

Narrator

I picked it up. Livia told me that Frens Ricter was on the line.

Petr Vectern

"With the majority behind the reforms, I don't think he can afford a sudden change of heart."

Petr Vectern

"He already supported the reforms, and the latest additions were something he's been campaigning for."

Petr Vectern

"I doubt that, Anton. I believe -- deep down inside -- he wants us to fail, so he can blame us for the failure and take the helm."

Narrator

Suddenly, the phone rang.

Petr Vectern

"Let's get some fresh air. There's not much we can do about the reforms now."

Player

"The President speaking."

Player

"Hello, Mr. Ricter."

Player

"What do you want?"

Frens Ricter

"I should have seen your true colors when you tried to cooperate with Mr. Kibener."

Frens Ricter

"Anyway... I'm calling to let you know that your sneaky little scheme won't work on us."

Frens Ricter

"I know what you're doing. You think you can pressure us by adding our proposed changes to Article 6 and 7."

Frens Ricter

"We will not fall for your trap."

Player

"What are you talking about, Mr. Ricter? There is no trap here. You're being paranoid."

Player

"I thought you wanted to add these changes to the proposal. What's the issue now?"

Player

"Come on, Mr. Ricter. The USP is willing to support the reforms you want. Are you really going to abandon your agenda all of a sudden?"

Player

"I thought you wanted me to add these changes to the proposal. What's the issue now?"

Frens Ricter

"The *reformist* agenda? Are you serious?"

Frens Ricter

"You think I'm stupid?"

Frens Ricter

"Sooner or later, everybody will realize that no true democratic reform will be a reality as long as your party is in charge."

Player

"I should have known you were a man who'd let go of tangible reforms for political gains."

Player

"So you never cared about the reforms and it was all a strategy to increase your power base, is that it?"

Player

"Let's calm down, Mr. Ricter. Why don't we arrange a meeting to discuss this in detail?"

Frens Ricter

"Don't try to spin things your way. You know exactly what I mean."

Frens Ricter

"It's too late for that, Mr. Rayne."

Frens Ricter

"I'll see you at next week's vote."

Player

"No, Petr. You go ahead. I'm not in the mood."

Player

"But what about you? What do you think will happen with our reforms?"

Petr Vectern

"You already know that without the USP there is no way of passing the Assembly. But I told you that it would be very risky, Anton."

Frens Ricter

"I hope everything is going well with the preparations for the vote next week."

Petr Vectern

"I hope all the bribery you've done won't go to waste."

Petr Vectern

"Come to think of it, your connection with the Oligarchs may still help us salvage the situation."

Player

"Of course we will."

Player

"Well, you heard wrong."

Player

"Unfortunately, it's true. Your suggested amendments to the citizenship section lost us the USP."

Player

"Yes. Most of the party will likely vote against the proposal."

Player

"Don't let rumors discourage you. As long as your party gives its complete support, there is always a possibility of passing it."

Player

"Yes. It looks very promising."

Player

"With your support, we will be making history, Mr. Ricter. You can count on the USP."

Player

"There were a few misunderstandings, but everything is going well at the moment."

Frens Ricter

"Well... About that..."

Frens Ricter

"You didn't mention more changes to the proposal. You know I support your latest additions to Article 6 and 7, but who gave you the authority to remove already agreed-upon terms?"

Frens Ricter

"On my way here, I learned you were suddenly removing the change to the election threshold. We've told you numerous times that a decrease to the threshold is a necessity."

Frens Ricter

"On my way here, I learned that you've suddenly decided to protect Tarquin Soll's Member of Honor privileges. We've told you numerous times that opening the door to putting Soll on trial is a necessity."

Frens Ricter

"On top of it, you also decided to protect Tarquin Soll's Member of Honor privileges."

Frens Ricter

"As expected. But discouraging nonetheless."

Frens Ricter

"Don't pin that on me. It wasn't me who told you to include those points at the last minute."

Frens Ricter

"Who are you kidding, Mr. Rayne?"

Player

"So, you knew about this?"

Player

"You don't seem too unhappy about this situation."

Player

"What are you trying to say, Mr. Ricter?"

Frens Ricter

"I didn't take it for granted that you would add the changes to Article 6 and 7, just because you joined the statement against them during the Ishval Ersen case."

Frens Ricter

"Frankly, I don't think it was discussed enough in detail before including them in the proposal."

Frens Ricter

"I think you are abusing the PFJP's willingness to reform, Mr. Rayne."

Frens Ricter

"I didn't think you were serious about adding the changes to Article 6 and 7. But just because you added changes that we campaign for doesn't mean I will support you no matter what."

Frens Ricter

Player

Player

Player

"You know how it is. A woman can't be trusted to do her job on her own."

Frens Ricter

Player

Player

Frens Ricter

"It seems you aren't up to date on the affairs of the PFJP."

Frens Ricter

"Ms. Suheil and most of our influential members are already against working with the USP. And they don't want me to give any more concessions."
